across Europe. These untapped sources reveal the extent to which parish clergy were embedded in their communities, particularly their kinship ties to villagers and their often contentious interactions with male parishioners and clerical colleagues. Defiant Priests highlights a clerical culture that embraced violence and illuminates how the parish church could become a battleground in which rivalries among clerics took place and young clerics learned from senior clergymen to meld the lay masculine ideals that were a part of their everyday culture with the privilege and authority of their profession.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aMarriagexReligious aspectsxCatholic ChurchxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aMarriagezSpainzCataloniaxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aMasculinityxReligious aspectsxCatholic ChurchxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aMasculinityzSpainzCataloniaxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 4aReligious Studies. 4aSpain. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aMasculinity, Medieval Iberia, Sexuality, Violence, Priests.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066587140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501707827?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501707827423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501707827/original  a978-3-11-066587-1  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK